			<ns0:name>k...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/112873510090665368075/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">Currently we have dynamic code modification tests, but these are implemented only as trusted tests. This means that we can not catch CPUID-related errors and we can not mock parts of validator in tests.

Example of bug caught by ASAN which can not be tested from untrusted code:
https://codereview.chromium.org/12576006/

Here we miss the range and when instructions are copied one additional byte is used. The end result (from untrusted code POV) is more or less the same (it introduces relatively-hard-to-exploit bug), but such bug can be caught easily with NaClCopyInstructionFunc mock.

It's not clear how important this test is: the functionality not covered by the existing tests is simple, but, as we can see, refactorings can introduce bugs there, too.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2013-03-07T14:45:43.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2013-03-07T14:35:46.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:status>New</ns2:status><ns2:cc>
